odansha manga]]\n[[Category:Polygon Pictures]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n\n{{anime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Prince Silversaddle", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor fixes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drifting_Dragons"}
{"title_page": "Vladimir Urbanovich", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vladimir Urbanovich\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Vladimir Nikolayevich Urbanovich\n| birth_date         = October 22, 1932\n| birth_place        = [[Usolye-Sibirskoye]], [[Irkutsk Oblast]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[USSR]]\n| occupation         = Opera singer, professor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| awards             = [[People\u2019s Artist of the RSFSR]]\n}}\n\n'''Vladimir Urbanovich''' (born 1932) is a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russian people|Russian]] [[baritone]], professor, and [[People\u2019s Artist of the RSFSR]] (1983).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vsp.ru/2016/11/22/kuznitsa-muzykalnyh-kadrov/|title=\u041a\u0443\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043a\u0430\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u0418\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0436 \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0451 80-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFrom 1965 onwards, Urbanovich was a soloist at the [[Novosibirsk Opera and Ballet Theatre|Novosibirsk Opera and Ballet Theater]]. He performed more than 60 parts of the baritone repertoire in opera classics and modern works. He toured in Poland (1986), Egypt (1993), Portugal (1996), participated in the production of Boris Godunov at the Baden Theater (Germany, 1994). He starred in several television film operas, including [[Youri Boutsko|Yuri Butsko]]'s ''Diary of a Madman''.\n\nHe also performed as a concert singer, and taught at the [[Novosibirsk Conservatory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kino-teatr.ru/teatr/acter/m/ros/383445/bio/|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0423\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|website=\u041a\u0438\u043d\u043e-\u0422\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440.\u0420\u0423|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novat.nsk.ru/en/news/news_media/sergey_kuzmin_samuray_ot_opery/|title=Sergey Kuzmin: The samurai of opera - NOVAT|website=novat.nsk.ru|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Russian opera singers]]\n[[Category:Soviet opera singers]]\n[[Category:Baritones]]\n[[Category:Russian operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vladimir Urbanovich\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Vladimir Nikolayevich Urbanovich\n| birth_date         = October 22, 1932\n| birth_place        = [[Usolye-Sibirskoye]], [[Irkutsk Oblast]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[USSR]]\n| occupation         = Opera singer, professor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| awards             = [[People\u2019s Artist of the RSFSR]]\n}}\n\n'''Vladimir Urbanovich''' (born 1932) is a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russian people|Russian]] [[baritone]], professor, and [[People\u2019s Artist of the RSFSR]] (1983).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vsp.ru/2016/11/22/kuznitsa-muzykalnyh-kadrov/|title=\u041a\u0443\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043a\u0430\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u0418\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0436 \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0451 80-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFrom 1965 onwards, Urbanovich was a soloist at the [[Novosibirsk Opera and Ballet Theatre|Novosibirsk Opera and Ballet Theater]]. He performed more than 60 parts of the baritone repertoire in opera classics and modern works. He toured in Poland (1986), Egypt (1993), Portugal (1996), participated in the production of Boris Godunov at the Baden Theater (Germany, 1994). He starred in several television film operas, including [[Youri Boutsko|Yuri Butsko]]'s ''Diary of a Madman''. \n\nHe also performed as a concert singer, and taught at the [[Novosibirsk Conservatory]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kino-teatr.ru/teatr/acter/m/ros/383445/bio/|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0423\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|website=\u041a\u0438\u043d\u043e-\u0422\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440.\u0420\u0423|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novat.nsk.ru/en/news/news_media/sergey_kuzmin_samuray_ot_opery/|title=Sergey Kuzmin: The samurai of opera - NOVAT|website=novat.nsk.ru|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Russian opera singers]]\n[[Category:Soviet opera singers]]\n[[Category:Baritones]]\n[[Category:Russian operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladimir_Urbanovich"}
